^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well done by everyone. Let's first talk about why I bid 3D as opposed to a DONT double. I did that for the same reason you always preempt. It gets in the opponents' way. I am not sure they get to 6 otherwise, but 3D made it very difficult and 4D by my partner was an excellent law of total tricks bid. We take 8 tricks, down 2 doubled, so only -300.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What should double by West mean? It certainly should not be penalty. It is not exactly Stayman either. It just shows some points. I don't necessarily recommend you play this, but Marty Bergen says any doubles of preempts of 3D, 3H, or 3S are "Thrump" doubles. They specifically deliver the following message. "Partner, I have points, but nothing clear cut to bid and I do not have a diamond stopper. I would like you to bid 3N with a diamond stopper." |
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, had E/W been playing Thrump doubles, and had my partner not bid 4D East would bid 3N over the Thrump double and that makes as well. Why might 3N be better than the 4-4 heart fit? Bergen's reasoning is as follows:
4-4 fits are dangerous with a bad trump break and you often get a bad trump break after a preempt. So, 3N is often the right place to play.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let's see what a possible auction is if I don't bid 3D. I like the following auction 1N-2C-2H-4D. 4D bid by West would be a splinter in diamonds, confirming hearts and then they might get to six  because the splinter implies slam interest. If West had no slam interest, (for example, say a 10 point hand with a singleton diamond), West would simply bid 4H. So, when you splinter, you are saying you are interested in slam. You should not splinter if you are not interested in slam.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


