^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about Shatha's excellent line of play. First, let's count the tricks--1 spade 2 hearts and a diamond. So, 3 more tricks are needed. On a really good day, you can take 4 diamonds and certainly taking 2 diamonds is possible so long as west has the club Ace. Therefore, starting with diamonds is fine. Once East shows the 10 of diamonds on the Ace, south made the correct play of finessing the 7 at trick 2. Why is that? |
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well some of you are familiar with what is known as the "law of restricted choice." Typically, that law applies when you are missing the Q and J. Say you have a suit A10xxx in dummy and Kxxx in your hand. If you play the K and the J or Q drops on your right you should assume it is singleton and lead low to the 10 at trick 2. That play works around 75% of the time. It is not intuitive, but it is true. The doubleton QJ is very rare.|
